In that article, the assumptions are the same as those in Theorem 1, except that u may be complex-valued.
Thus, as in the case of bounded V, Theorem 1 illustrates that better estimates hold in the real-valued planar setting.

As illustrated by the following example, Theorem 1 is sharp (up to \varepsilon) for all N\in(0,2).
Fix N\in(0,2), then set u(z)=\exp\left(-\left|z\right|^{1-\frac{N}{2}}\right).
A computation shows that u satisfies (1.4) where

