satisfies \left|V(z)\right|\lesssim\left|z\right|^{-N}.
On the other hand, for any \beta>0, with u(z)=\left|z\right|^{-\beta} on \left|z\right|>1, we see that \displaystyle\Delta u=\beta^{2}\left|z\right|^{-\beta-2} and therefore u satisfies (1.4) on an exterior domain with V(z):=\beta^{2}\left|z\right|^{-2}.
In particular, we may not have exponential behavior when V decays fast enough, which explains why we restrict ourselves to N<2.

To prove Theorem 1, we use an iterative argument that is reminiscent of the one in [Dav14], see also [LW14, DKW19, Dav20a, Dav25].
To initialize the iteration, we apply a quantitative estimate of the form (1.2) with \beta=1.
This result, which verifies Landis’ conjecture in the real-valued planar setting, was originally proved by Logunov, Malinnikova, Nadirashvili, and Nazarov in [LMNN20], and we formulate it in Theorem 3 below.
The iteration argument then relies on repeated applications of Proposition 2 which is proved using the ideas from [LMNN20].
Roughly speaking, Proposition 2 shows that if an estimate like (1.2) holds with \beta=\beta\_{0}, then for some x\_{1} with \left|x\_{1}\right|\gg\left|x\_{0}\right|, another estimate like (1.2) holds with x\_{0} replaced by x\_{1} and \beta=\beta\_{1}\in\left[1,\beta\_{0}\right].
When \beta\_{0}=1, Proposition 2 isn’t useful, but when \beta\_{0}>1, we can decrease the exponent, i.e., make \beta\_{1}<\beta\_{0}.
Therefore, to benefit from the iteration argument, we need to transform to a situation where \beta\_{0}>1.
We observe that if u is composed with the real-variable version of the conformal transformation z\mapsto z^{\alpha}, then the new function also satisfies a Schrödinger equation.
By choosing \alpha>1 appropriately, we can ensure that the new potential function is bounded and that the new solution function satisfies a version of (1.2) with \beta>1.
By repeatedly applying Proposition 2 to the transformed equation, we can make \beta arbitrarily close to 1.
Finally, to reach the conclusion, we undo the change of variables.

